# pyProbe

pyProbe is a Python-based application for acquisition of autofluorescence lifetime data using the TimeTagger Ultra from Swabian Instruments.

## Author

João Lagarto — Last updated 2026-03-10

## Features

### Laser Control (Harp — Becker & Hickl)
- Laser intensity and frequency control via serial (COM5 by default)
- Laser enable/disable interlock
- Automatic laser on/off at measurement start/stop

### FLIM Data Acquisition (TimeTagger Ultra — Swabian Instruments)
- Two-channel time-correlated single photon counting (TCSPC)
- Real-time count rate monitoring (laser sync, 2 detectors, external trigger)
- Configurable histogram: number of bins, bin width, temporal offsets, dead times
- Adjustable integration time and number of measurements
- Holdout timer before acquisition start
- Acquisition modes:
  - **Solution** — limited measurements (200), histogram only, no holdout
  - **In vivo / Ex vivo** — extended acquisition with image processing and holdout

### Camera Integration (FLIR — Spinnaker SDK)
- Hardware and software trigger modes
- Adjustable exposure time and white balance
- Configurable ROI (width, height, x/y offset)
- Real-time spot tracking with multiple image processing modes
- Background capture and subtraction

### Detector Control
- Hamamatsu SPAD detector ON/OFF via Harp

### LED Ring Light Control (NeoPixel via Arduino)
- Serial control (COM6 by default) over state (on/off) and brightness

### Data Saving
- FLIM histograms saved as HDF5 (`.h5`) per channel
- Measurement log (histogram indices, timestamps)
- Video of acquired frames with frame log (spot coordinates, measurement indices)
- Snapshots

## Installation

### Requirements
- Python 3.10 (required for Spinnaker wheel)
- Spinnaker SDK (FLIR) — wheel bundled at `spinnaker_python-3.2.0.62-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl`

### Setup

```bash
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

> Note: The Spinnaker wheel is installed from the local file as specified in `requirements.txt`.

## Configuration

Edit `config.yaml` to set hardware parameters before launching:

| Section | Key parameters |
|---|---|
| `camera` | `device_id`, `exposure_time`, `trigger_mode`, `format`, `offset` |
| `harp` | `port` (e.g. COM5) |
| `time_tagger` | channel assignments, bin settings, delays, dead times, trigger levels |
| `led` | `power`, `enable` |
| `laser` | `power`, `enable` |
| `default_data_folder` | Root folder for data saving dialogs |

Arduino serial port defaults to `COM6`; override with `arduino_port` key in `config.yaml`.

## Running

```bash
python main.py
```

## Keyboard Shortcuts

| Key | Action |
|---|---|
| `F5` | Start measurement |
| `F9` | Stop measurement |
| `Ctrl+S` | Save data |

## Project Structure

```
pyProbe/
├── main.py                  # Entry point
├── config.yaml              # Hardware configuration
├── controllers/             # Hardware controllers (Harp, TimeTagger, Camera)
├── instruments/             # Low-level hardware wrappers
├── views/                   # PyQt5 GUI (MainWindow.py + MainWindow.ui)
├── workers/                 # QThread workers (Data, FLIM, CountRate, Camera)
└── utils/                   # DataSaver, ProcessingMode, helpers
```
